Before loading the data into one dataframe, the schema of each csv file needs checking to provide verification that they have the identical schema. Each file has the following columns Rental Id, Duration, Bike Id, End Date, EndStation Id, EndStation Name, Start Date, StartStation Id, and StartStation Name. However, some files such as "6. Journey Data Extract 25May14-21Jun14.csv" have 3 additional columns _c9, _c10, and _c11.

By looking at the unique values in the additional columns _c9, _c10, and _c11, there are only null values in this column. As the column only houses null values it is of no use and therefore is not required. Therefore, the schema of each file is suitable to one another.

Outliers¶

To be able to suitably test the project hypothesis, an establishment of what a valid bike ride needs to be defined. Bides that last in excess of a day can be questioned as valid rides whilst rides that last na incredibly small amount of time could be rides that have been mistakenly rented. To detect outliers, the Inter Quartile Range is used. The 25th and 75th percentiles of the duration column are first detected.

In [37]:
bikes_data.select('Duration').summary('25%','75%').show()

+-------+--------+
|summary|Duration|
+-------+--------+
|    25%|     480|
|    75%|    1320|
+-------+--------+
In [38]:
#Use approxQuantile to save on computational time with accepted error 0.15 
dur_upper = bikes_data.approxQuantile("Duration",[0.75],relativeError=0.15)
dur_lower = bikes_data.approxQuantile("Duration",[0.25],relativeError=0.15)
In [39]:
#Calculate the IQR
IQR = dur_upper[0] - dur_lower[0]
In [40]:
print(f'The approximate upper quartile is: {dur_upper[0]}.')
print(f'The approximate lower quartile is: {dur_lower[0]}.')
print(f'The inter quartile range is: {IQR}.')

The approximate upper quartile is: 1260.0.
The approximate lower quartile is: 480.0.
The inter quartile range is: 780.0.

The upper and lower bounds can be calculated. The lower bound is negative and therefore not appropriate to be used. Instead the lower bound can be set as 30 so that all rentals that last longer than 30 seconds are kept

In [41]:
print(dur_upper[0] + 1.5 * IQR)
print(dur_lower[0] - 1.5 * IQR)

2430.0
-690.0
In [42]:
dur_upbound = dur_upper[0] + 1.5 * IQR
dur_lowbound = 30
In [43]:
bikes_data = bikes_data.filter(
    (bikes_data.Duration > dur_lowbound) & (bikes_data.Duration < dur_upbound)
)

Joining Through Aggregation¶

Aggregation is used to obtain the mean value of duration of bike rides per hour per day and also the number of bike rides per hour per day.

#Group by date and hour and obtain duration statistics
Bikes_sts = bikes_data.groupby(['start','hour']).agg(
    
    sum("Duration").alias("Sum of Bike Ride Durations"),
    avg("Duration").alias("Average Bike Ride Duration"),
    min("Duration").alias("Minimum Bike Ride Duration"),
    max("Duration").alias("Maximum Bike Ride Duration")
)

Traffic volume groups can be created by grouping the total count of motor vehicles into the following groups:

  • 0% <= x <= 20% -> Very Low
  • 20% < x < 40% -> Low
  • 40% <= x < 60% -> Medium
  • 60% <= x < 80% -> High
  • 80% <= x <= 100% -> Very High

The very low category contains values at the 20% percentile as the minimum and 20% values are close.

In [123]:
#Obtain the 20th, 40th, 60th, and 80th percentiles with a relative error or 0.2
groups = Bikes_Traffic.approxQuantile('Total Count of Motor Vehicles', [0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8], 0.2)
In [115]:
#Obtain the maximum and minimum values
max_count=Bikes_Traffic.agg({"Total Count of Motor Vehicles":"max"}).collect()[0]['max(Total Count of Motor Vehicles)']
min_count=Bikes_Traffic.agg({"Total Count of Motor Vehicles":"min"}).collect()[0]['min(Total Count of Motor Vehicles)']
In [99]:
# Amend column to double type
Bikes_Traffic = Bikes_Traffic.withColumn("Total Count of Motor Vehicles", 
                                 Bikes_Traffic["Total Count of Motor Vehicles"]
                                  .cast('double'))
In [139]:
# Create column based on conditions
Bikes_Traffic = Bikes_Traffic.withColumn(
    'Traffic Group',
     when((col("Total Count of Motor Vehicles") >= min_count) & (col("Total Count of Motor Vehicles") <= groups[0])  , 'Very Low')
    .when((col("Total Count of Motor Vehicles") > groups[0]) & (col('Total Count of Motor Vehicles') < groups[1]) , 'Low')
    .when((col("Total Count of Motor Vehicles") >= groups[1]) & (col('Total Count of Motor Vehicles') < groups[2]) , 'Medium')
    .when((col("Total Count of Motor Vehicles") >= groups[2]) & (col('Total Count of Motor Vehicles') < groups[3]) , 'High')
    .when((col("Total Count of Motor Vehicles") >= groups[3]) & (col('Total Count of Motor Vehicles') <= max_count) , 'Very High')
    .otherwise('Very Low')
)

To increase interpretability and better represent the distributions, feature scaling & transformation can be done.

In [154]:
#Standardising the Bike Count variable
Bike_Traff_pd['Standardised Bike Count'] = (
    Bike_Traff_pd['Bike Rental Count'] - Bike_Traff_pd['Bike Rental Count'].mean()) / Bike_Traff_pd['Bike Rental Count'].std()

# Log-Transforming both traffic and bike count variables
Bike_Traff_pd['Log Traffic Count'] = np.log(Bike_Traff_pd['Total Count of Motor Vehicles'])
Bike_Traff_pd['Log Bike Count'] = np.log(Bike_Traff_pd['Bike Rental Count'])
